AB  - The overall outcome of the Emergency Food and Nutrition Security Project for South Sudan is moderately satisfactory, with moderately satisfactory Bank performance and modest evaluation and monitoring quality. The Project provided several lessons: 1. As the Bank increases its support to FCV (Fragility, Conflict, and Violence) countries, it will need to establish protocols for humanitarian emergency response projects; 2. FCV countries are usually not data-rich environments; 3. Flexibility in Project Design and Implementation; 4. Technical assistance vs. capacity building; 5. The results framework should be designed in accordance with the existing circumstances of the borrower nation; 6. Additional resources are required for supervision in FCV countries because of the lower capacity of clients; 7. Humanitarian operations can lay the foundation for development; 8. Prepositioning of supplies related to health, nutrition, WASH (Water Sanitation and Hygiene), etc. before the rainy season saves on logistics costs.
