AB  - Ratings for the Resilience and Disaster Risk Management Project for Malawi were as follows: outcomes were moderately satisfactory, the Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and the monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: the project started as a drought recovery project and after the AF changed to a flood recovery and disaster management project. The decision at AF of deleting all indicators (though achieved) made the AF appear to be a new project. It would be important for project teams to ensure continuity of the project storyline after a restructuring to maintain the focus of the project. There were challenges in complying with Bank safeguard requirements due to low capacity, which was not adequately mitigated for at appraisal; safeguard implementation improved when the Bank provided more hands-on support. Based on this experience, RCRP2 is taking a more proactive approach and is providing Hands-On Expanded Implementation Support (HEIS) to the GoM in safeguard implementation. In addition to supporting the PIU, the HEIS is also being used to support training at the district level to improve sustainability. The Project was successful in engaging communities through many avenues, including through the establishment and training of WUAs, investments in community assets such as boreholes and irrigation, and the formation of local DRM committees. This participatory approach ensured that the project generated a strong partnership between beneficiaries and implementers, and helped improve implementation and led to locally adapted infrastructure. For example, community feedback was used to adjust infrastructure designs, such as for the Thangadzi West flood protection structure.
