AB  - Ratings for the Smallholder Agriculture Development and Commercialization Project for Angola were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: the farmer field school (FFS) experience yielded several valuable lessons relating to the need for evolutionary flexibility, a clear exit strategy for the principal service provider, and the importance of accompanying FFS trainings with different levels of investment support to maximize benefits from the trainings. A low-capacity environment where certain skills are highly demanded (procurement, environmental and social safeguards) requires upfront planning and adequate mitigation measures. It might be helpful to define subsidiary targets tailored to various farming systems within the project area. Innovations, such as internally capitalized community funds can amplify the impact of input support programs. Although it is yet to undergo the test of time, the block farming concept can help trigger the emergence of functional value chains. In the case of low institutional irrigation capacity, it is better to start with individual small-scale, low technology irrigation investments, before gradually embarking on larger schemes as institutional capacity grows.
