L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_BI-Burundi_Coffee_Sector_Competitiveness_Project_--_P151869_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2022.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Coffee Sector Competitiveness Project for Burundi were as follows: outcome was unsatisfactory, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality (M and E) was modest. Some lessons learned included: in a fragility, conflict, and violence (FCV) context where the political environment can be uncertain and government policies can change abruptly, such as in the case in Burundi, it is necessary to have flexible procedures in place under World Bank projects to allow a quick transfer of undisbursed funds across the portfolio when conditions for a particular operation to continue are not met. Producer incentives: a necessary condition for the coffee sector (or any other crop sector predicated on smallholder production) to thrive, and for benefits to eventually accrue to all parties, is for farm level prices to be set at a sufficiently high level to incentivize producers. Financial transactions: the project demonstrated that timely payments need to be made along the value chain between actors, especially at upstream level from coffee washing stations (CWSs) to producers, to keep the required level of incentives with the producers. In the context of a coffee rejuvenation program, intercropping during the gestation period when new coffee plants and stumped trees are growing and not yet fully productive, is a good agricultural practice that needs to be systematically disseminated and adopted. Last mile good rural infrastructure is critical to quickly link producers to the point of first treatment and local markets following crop harvest.
