L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P128434_29269473_ICR_2017.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Climate Change Development Policy Operations Project for Mozambique were as follows: outcomes were satisfactory, the risk to development outcome was substantial, the Bank performance was satisfactory, and the Borrower performance was moderately satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: the cross-sectoral nature of climate risks and their impacts typically affect several sectors of a country’s economy, as in the case of Mozambique, where for example the occurrence of a severe flood impacts not only agricultural production, basic infrastructure, and access to services, but also immediately affects government’s fiscal space. This requires policy responses and decisions involving key economic and line agencies working together to reach a common understanding of the challenges and opportunities, assess urgency and tradeoffs among options and their socio-economic implications, and prioritize actions. This is conceptually appealing but practically difficult to achieve because of institutional fragmentation and rigidities, as well as political economy issues. Selectivity and sequencing of policy reforms could help sectors build capacity at their own pace, and focus Bank resources where most incremental gains can be achieved. As indicated in the previous two lessons, while effective climate change policy reform requires a deep and sustained engagement on the part of the Bank--and development partners--coupled with a national cross-sectoral platform, it is important to ensure that the sectors selected for reform have achieved minimum readiness, and that they have access to adequate support to move as quickly as possible from planning to financing to implementation. The Bank team supporting the Mozambique DPO series may well have faced this issue and found itself at times spread too thin. Therefore, an assessment at the outset of trade-offs regarding the scope, sequencing and depth of the supported reforms is a worthwhile endeavor.
KW  - Mozambique
KW  - worldbank
