AB  - Ratings for the Water for Agro-Pastoral Productivity and Resilience Project for Somalia were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: gradually increasing the scale of World Bank operations in fragility, conflict, and violence (FCV) contexts, from activities trust fund financed ASAs and smaller pilot projects such as the WAPP, contributes to improved implementation efficiency. In rural areas, a development approach that prioritizes the development of multiple-use water sources generates greater multisectoral benefits than a conventional water supply project design. Implementing projects through government systems in FCV contexts, while complex, can enhance government capacities and foster trust between citizens and state. Accommodating additional community needs and priorities can help foster trust and social cohesion in FCV contexts. The use of technology innovations for infrastructure site selection combines with a community driven development (CDD) approach are essential for ownership and sustainability.
