AB  - The Community Markets for Conservation (COMACO) Landscape Management Project (CLMP) was a pilot project designed to apply a climate-smart landscape management approach for addressing drivers of deforestation. It provides lessons that could be useful in a future opportunity to scale up an integrated approach to jurisdictional landscape management in the Eastern Province of Zambia. The project is the first of its kind in Africa linking sustainable agriculture and forest conservation through results-based payments. The CLMP indicates that carbon finance is a catalyst to achieving results. Integrated landscape management projects can benefit from the use of blended finance instruments that use public sector finance to scale up private investments for emissions reduction. Some lessons learned included: cross-sectoral coordination is an important factor to successful carbon project implementation. Strong partnerships between implementation actors and local stakeholders should be promoted at all levels to improve project delivery and build sustainability. Access to market incentivizes sustainable agricultural land management (SALM) adoption and is important to achieving results. There is potential for scaling up the CLMP model, but this will rely on viable public and private sources of finance. Use of innovative approaches to deliver project objectives contribute to better assimilation and buy-in of beneficiaries.
