AB  - Ratings for the Regional Pastoral Livelihoods Resilience Project for Eastern and Southern Africa were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: the regional approach of the project was useful in addressing conflict management, harmonized disease control actions and identification of investments in jointly used cross-border water and market infrastructure. The establishment of joint planning and monitoring platforms between project countries, facilitated the exchange of information, lessons and knowledge and skills that created an environment for the project to be effectively implemented. The implementation of activities in conflict prone areas added to the project’s complexity, however, interventions that yielded high enough returns to rival investments in livestock created alternative livelihoods that minimized conflicts in the region. The role of the community animal health workers (CAHW) was critical to expanding extension support for livestock services in the project areas. Building up the capacity of the CAHWs ensured that the support services will be retained within the communities even in the absence of project support. Livestock water resource investments made focused mainly on water supply for livestock, however, there was an emergence of human settlements near developed water points, which, if properly managed, can contribute towards a more sustainable management of such water resources. The introduction of alternative livelihoods was to diversify into activities that were less prone to risk, providing a buffer to pastoral communities to better withstand and recover more quickly from shocks including conflict.
