AB  - Ratings of Livestock Development Animal Health Project for China were as follows: outcome was moderately unsatisfactory, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was negligible. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) Addressing challenges of livestock production and productivity require a multipronged approach and a balanced attention to their main drivers or constraints; (ii) Institutional strengthening takes time and a project should not rely too heavily on expected reforms to achieve certain results; (iii) Simple and well adapted procedures, mechanisms and template for the preparation and approval of sub‐grants are critical not only to facilitate and accelerate the process but also, to ensure that the risk of elite capture is minimized; (iv) It is important to ensure clarity upfront on indicator definitions and scope to avoid ambiguities and minimize mid‐term revisions to indicators unless the scope of the project has changed; and (v) Results expectations should be realistic when project implementation relies exclusively on country systems to avoid setting the project up for eventual failure.
