AB  - Ratings for the Inclusive Growth and Fiscal Management Development Policy Operation for Kenya were as follows: overall outcome, relevance of prior actions, and achievement of objectives (efficacy) was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: the need to ensure a triumvirate of support among key stakeholders including strong buy-in from higher level decision makers in government, strong senior management support at the World Bank, and support from development partners. The importance of identifying the confluence between government priorities and those of the World Bank. The importance of strong government co-ordination role, spear-headed by the national treasury. An important factor in the successful execution of the reform program was the strong technical capacity and reform appetite that exists among the policy making civil servant cadre in the Ministries, Departments, and Agencies (MDAs). The program illustrates the advantages of a strong analytical foundation for the choice of prior actions and the benefits of complementary support from World Bank operations (ASA, investment project financing (IPFs) and PFoRs).
