L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P177460-P179141_40030582_ICR_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the First and Second Foundational Economic Governance Reforms Development Policy Financing (DPF) Project for Democratic Republic of Congo were as follows: overall outcomes and achievement of objectives (efficacy) were moderately satisfactory, and relevance of prior actions and Bank performance was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: this first DPF series supported the promulgation and implementation of the new Telecom law, the implementation of a Treasury function at the Ministry of Finance, and reforms in the governance of the energy and water utilities with the competitive recruitment of key positions. However, it required a detailed understanding of the political economy, perseverance, and bold positioning. For instance, it was made clear to the client that the failure of the executive to enact the best practice Telecom Law supported by Bank TA and passed by the parliament would undermine the credibility of any reform that entails the adoption of a draft law by the cabinet. Recommendation: DPF TTLs need to identify and work with champions, stay the course when vested interests threaten to undermine reforms, and maintain a focus on effective implementation through programmatic support. Management needs to support TTLs by creating an environment conducive to informed risk-taking. DPFs in a low-capacity environment must be accompanied by technical assistance and/or investment projects. Most of the prior actions were supported by World Bank projects. Coordination with other donors was also important, for example in non-tax revenue collection where AfDB played an important role. The Central African Forest Initiative was instrumental in supporting forestry governance reforms, as the World Bank was re-engaging in the sector. Pressure from the IMF helped move the EITI agenda forward. However, investment projects are not always fully aligned with the timetable required by a DPF. This contributed to the delays in the de-concentration of spending. A new two-operation series approved by the Board in May 2025. The program supports continued de-concentration of public spending as well as further reforms in procurement and SOE governance, including special attention to the electricity utility. It also introduces asset declaration and promotes private sector development.
