AB  - Ratings for the Resilient Landscapes and Livelihoods Project (RLLP) for Ethiopia were as follows: outcome and Bank performance were satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: a strategic lesson from Sustainable Land Management Project Phase 1 (SLMP-I) and SLMP-II reflected in the design and implementation of RLLP is the need to provide reasonable time to achieve the stabilization of degraded areas, complemented by mechanisms and supporting elements to allow watershed communities to evolve from project-based assistance and adopt and consolidate sustainable management of restored landscapes through government programs. In the design of any NRM project, security of land ownership or user rights represents a key factor for strengthening community incentives for investment in and maintenance of SLM interventions. Highly decentralized SLM implementation is a major factor of project success. Fiduciary lessons regarding the overall support to the SLM Program highlight the importance of: (a) aligning project budgeting systems with the Government of Ethiopia (GoE) budget calendar; (b) including the costs of environmental mitigation measures in subproject designs; and (c) providing adequate resources to upgrade planning, budgeting, and monitoring of inputs and outputs that are essential for decentralized operations.
