L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_MZ-Mozambique_Forest_Investment_Project_--_P160033_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2023.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Forest Investment Project for Mozambique (MozFIP) were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: the project design can critically affect the quality and sustainability of forest plantations with rotation period longer than the project length. MozFIP demonstrated the need to improve the selection criteria of project beneficiaries to avoid allocation of questionably high subsidies to larger, already established commercial enterprises. Use of private specialized service providers for field-intensive projects presents a cost-effective alternative to ensure adequate support to beneficiaries during project implementation. The matching grant system did not generate the desired results for the project. Although the assessment suggests that this unsatisfactory performance is largely due to the extremely short implementation period of the scheme, the criteria, and conditions for the effective use of matching grants should be further evaluated to determine if such instrument represents an appropriate mechanism to contribute to the objectives of forest-related subprojects. he encouraging results recorded from the successful implementation of the gender-based gender action learning system (GALS) within MOZFIP will suggest the convenience of mainstreaming the initiative in other projects, particularly those associated with agroforestry systems, as is now being adopted by Sustainable Rural Economy Program (MozRural) and Northern Mozambique Rural Resilience Project (MozNorte), not only for the rural communities but also within fisheries communities.
KW  - Mozambique
