AB  - Ratings for the Forest and Nature Conservation Project for Democratic Republic of Congo were as follows: outcomes was moderately unsatisfactory, global environment facility (GEO) outcomes were moderately unsatisfactory, risk to development outcome was high, risk to GEO outcome was high, Bank performance was unsatisfactory, and Borrower performance was unsatisfactory. Some lessons learned included: relying on policy or regulatory pre-conditions, such as the government decrees for the timber production control and marketing program (PCPCB) and for community forestry, poses risks, as commitment to meeting those preconditions can change over time. Complex projects in challenging settings require the best project management talent the Bank can muster. Investments in community income-generating opportunities in forest areas offer promising avenues for poverty reduction. Engagements in governance issues in settings with a complex political economy should perhaps consider phased approaches, with incentives for delivery, such as disbursements linked to performance. Reliance on co-financing is inherently risky in countries with constrained fiscal space. Cost-sharing between different financial sources can create obstacles for disbursements.
