AB  - Ratings for the Accelerating Reforms for an Inclusive and Resilient Recovery Development Policy Financing in Kenya were as follows: outcomes were satisfactory, the relevance of prior actions was satisfactory, and the Bank's performance was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: while this operation was being prepared, the world was experiencing a high degree of economic, political, and social uncertainty due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Even after the initial 2021 recovery and as vaccines are applied, new strains of the disease appeared. In this environment, the team adjusted the operation to reflect new government priorities, while at the same time keeping the focus on building a stronger healthcare system. For example, as described, pillars were modified as well as some triggers which became prior actions. Although the size of the policy matrix raised initial concerns, it was an opportunity to build consensus around policy reforms which had already reached a point of maturity. The June 2024 youth-led protests opposing tax reforms under the proposed FY2024-25 budget highlight the need to further strengthen the political and social risk evaluation of reforms supported by future operations. Although not directly related to WBG operations in this case, these events pose the need to strengthen and confirm the public consultation process by Government for future reforms and maximize the assent from the population. This is not restricted to DPFs and could extend to other World Bank financing instruments including PforRs and IPFs. The protests have strengthened the awareness for greater accountability on needed reforms, such as expenditure control and anticorruption measures that could contribute to the achievement of results indicators agreed upon in future DPFs.
