L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P164431_40019742_ICR_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Smallholder Irrigated Agriculture and Market Access Project for Mozambique were as follows: outcomes were moderately satisfactory, the Bank performance was satisfactory, and the monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: irrigation kits using solar-powered pumps can be effective in enabling farmers to generate high returns, especially when used for high-value, off-season vegetables. The project distributed a pump per two farmers to maximize returns on the investment. Farmers obtained high vegetable yields and high returns, especially in the off-season. This arrangement needs to be explored further to assess the impact on maintenance, as the pumps were distributed late in project implementation, preventing a full assessment. Irrigated agriculture provides a great opportunity for fostering private sector participation in financing agricultural inputs. Unreliable weather patterns create hesitation in financing agriculture, including from agro input dealers. However, with irrigation, many agro-dealers were willing to provide inputs to farmers. Although the matching grants activities under the project did not take off, private input supply arrangements stepped in to fill the gap and are more sustainable. In the 2021 project restructuring, fiduciary responsibilities were transferred to the FNDS, while INIR retained the planning, regulatory, and coordination roles. This institutional arrangement proved effective in supporting climate-sensitive reforms. INIR with its sector-specific expertise and mandate to oversee irrigation in the country, demonstrated strong responsiveness to the need for updating institutional frameworks and took a proactive approach in designing irrigation schemes for rehabilitation damaged the extreme climate events that could be adapted throughout the project lifecycle, particularly to mitigate climate risks such as the impacts of cyclones. This level of technical foresight and adaptive responsiveness may have been less likely if FNDS had taken on these technical roles. This experience underscores the value of leveraging the technical expertise and institutional knowledge of sector-specific agencies to enhance climate resilience in irrigation infrastructure and planning.
KW  - Mozambique
