AB  - Ratings for the Sustainable Landscape Management Project for Madagascar were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: the project’s innovative nature highlighted the significance of a flexible design and a practical approach to integrated landscape management. Maintenance of irrigation schemes can be hindered by inadequate user fee collection and ineffective maintenance funds for the functioning of community organizations. Institutional strengthening through capacity building of government staff, communities, and farmer groups contribute to sustainability of project outcomes. Community management expectations were found to be unrealistic within the project's timeframe, as communities require more time to build expertise and mobilize funds. The payment for ecosystem services (PES) component was overly complex and ambitious, resulting in delayed payments beyond the project’s duration and causing imbalances between upstream and downstream communities.
