AB  - Ratings for the Agriculture and Natural Resources Landscape Management Project for Mozambique were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: the landscape small emerging commercial farmer (SECF) model was effective in enhancing smallholder farmers’ capacity to use knowledge and adopt sustainable agricultural practices and technologies to increase agricultural productivity. The lack of comprehensive evaluation report and the impact study at the end of the project implementation was a missed opportunity as the project experience suggest that the Landscape model has a great potential to be effective in promoting sustainable market-oriented agriculture and simultaneously investing on sustainable natural resources management. The matching grants mechanism was a successful instrument for financing farmers to purchase equipment and other modern inputs. However, the low adherence of financial institutions to provide complementary finance to SECFs needs to be further evaluated. The project developed a weather-based insurance product, which appeared to be very attractive to farmers. Successful scale up of operations requires a realistic assessment of the existing capacities based on lessons learned.
