AB  - Ratings for the First and Second Agriculture Development Policy Operations Projects for Mozambique were as follows: outcomes were satisfactory, risk to development outcome was substantial, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and Borrower performance was moderately satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: reforms actions are not business as usual and requires the commitment of a government that is reform minded for it to happen. Institutional leverage is key to effective coordination and monitoring of progress in the reform actions supported. It is equally important to ensure that any risks related to data availability are identified and accounted for upfront before concluding project preparation. Defining development policy operation (DPO) series objectives in concrete and measurable terms and linking them to implementation on the ground can improve demonstration of impact and enhance attribution. In a context where sector DPO series seldom reach completion, it is important to ensure that this risk is mitigated in the way that reform actions are sequenced. In this instance, the termination of the third operation in the series was a missed opportunity to consolidate on the gains of preceding operations.
