L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P117635_40079232_ICR_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings of the Kenya Water Security and Climate Resilience Project for Kenya were as follows: outcome was moderately satisfactory, Bank performance was moderately unsatisfactory, and M&E quality was substantial. Lessons learned include that combining large-scale irrigation investments with broad institutional and policy reforms in a single investment operation can dilute focus and reduce efficiency; large irrigation schemes are better implemented as stand-alone projects, while legislative and policy reforms that require Cabinet or Parliamentary action are more suitable for Development Policy Financing. Land acquisition is a critical path item that demands early and sustained attention; future operations should align engineering and land teams from the outset to sequence site handover effectively, communicate compensation arrangements to farmers clearly and consistently, plan and fund crop compensation in sync with construction schedules, strengthen institutional and legal capacity, secure financing early, and maintain continuous coordination. Irrigation strategy should pivot toward farmer-led irrigation to achieve faster, scalable impact, with any necessary large-scale schemes delivered through a two-stage approach: Stage 1 to complete feasibility, detailed design, and land acquisition, and Stage 2 to execute construction and embed sustainability measures such as agricultural support and operation and maintenance. Technical outcomes must be matched by robust financial planning for operation and maintenance; institutions such as the Water Resources Authority require reliable revenue and timely regulatory support to sustain hydrometeorological networks and early warning systems, and irrigation schemes need predictable financing through well designed irrigation service fees or public transfers. Clear financial strategies that identify funding sources, assess revenue potential, and set affordable, sustainable pricing can strengthen accountability and ownership, improve service performance over time, and secure the long-term benefits of water investments.
KW  - Kenya
