AB  - Ratings of Agro-Pastoral Productivity and Markets Development Project (PRODEMA) for Burundi were as follows: outcome was moderately satisfactory, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) PRODEMA under its specific community driven development (CDD) design has, over a decade, successfully combined support to agriculture production, infrastructure development, and access to market; (ii) The introduction of innovations in agriculture, particularly at the processing stage, which often requires sophisticated equipment, should be carried out with a sufficient lead time, so that the equipment can be tested and made functional, and the operators can be trained; (iii) The integration of crop and animal husbandry permits to achieve a symbiotic production process leading to greater productivity; (iv) The solidarity chain regarding animal allocation further to the first round of project support is instrumental to ensure that benefits are widely shared in the larger rural community; (v) Market analysis is a must for the development of value chains when surpluses are expected to be generated; it needs to be conducted in realistic fashion adapted to the local market context; and (vi) A specific legislation to establish Producer Organizations (POs) is needed to accompany development efforts and ensure that producers are in command.
