AB  - Ratings of Land Husbandry, Water Harvesting and Hillside Irrigation Project for Rwanda were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) The Project proved that site specific conditions were critical for determining what type of land husbandry package should be applied; (ii) Whole value chain interventions, and public-private partnership for sustainable results; (iii) Effective cooperation between Government and development partners; (iv) Building good governance systems; (v) The government’s hillside intensification objectives could not have been successfully achieved without the strong ownership and engagement of farmers in production and marketing activities; (vi) Involvement of local leaders (village leaders and GRC leaders) was key in the resolution of conflicts over plots among neighbors, land owners and owner of assets on that land, as well as in the resolution of inter-family issues over ownership of assets or of social issues, such as the proper management or use of compensation funds received by some displaced Project Affected Person (PAPs).
