AB  - Ratings for the Agricultural Productivity Program for Southern Africa Project for Angola, Lesotho were as follows: outcomes were moderately satisfactory; Bank performance was moderately satisfactory; and monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: the APPSA experience reaffirmed that a regional approach to agricultural research and technology dissemination offers significant benefits, including shared expertise, economies of scale, and harmonized standards. However, it also highlighted the inherent complexity of multi-country operations, requiring strong institutional readiness, clear governance arrangements, and early government commitment. It is recommended that sufficient preparation time be allocated to align national policies, clarify governance and coordination mechanisms, and secure commitments from finance and agriculture ministries before implementation. Infrastructure and research capacity risk underutilization without operational budgets and post-project support. Sustainability planning and government commitments must be built into project design. It is recommended that future projects require government commitments for long-term operating costs and staffing, base infrastructure on needs assessments, and include detailed sustainability plans during preparation. Governments must commit to performance benchmarks and monitoring systems to track utilization and impact. Private sector participation in research, seed systems, and technology transfer was limited. It is recommended that future projects identify clear entry points for private engagement, such as co-financing seed multiplication, fostering agritech partnerships, and establishing public-private innovation platforms, to strengthen sustainability and support the commercialization of research outputs.
