AB  - Ratings for the Land Bank Financial Intermediation Project for South Africa were as follows: outcome was highly unsatisfactory, Bank performance was moderately unsatisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: lines of credit that involve new products or strategic changes within the implementing entity will benefit from components that provide resources to support these changes. World Bank projects that support Development Finance Institution (DFIs) that are not adequately supervised should address this as part of the project or prior to project approval. The World Bank should ensure that replacing subsidized lending instruments with ones that move towards full cost recovery is carefully studied to ensure that lending without subsidies is viable. For credit line projects that focus on specific sectors, it is important to include a co- Task Team Leader (TTL) from both the relevant sector and finance, competitiveness, and innovation (FCI) global practice (GP) as well as have the relevant ministry involved in the project implementation arrangement. Providing financing to entities that depend significantly on commercial borrowings exposes the project implementation to significant risks that are extraneous to the project. There are gaps that were identified in the World Bank’s management of local part of the project implementation that should be reviewed.
