AB  - Ratings for the Smallholder Agriculture Development Project for Lesotho were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: changing mindsets about commercial agriculture is challenging but an achievable task with right investments and institutional support. Adequate assessment of enabling conditions is critical to achieve intended results and impacts. service providers (SPs) played a major role to facilitate and support the development of subproject activities. Building resilience, including from climate shocks, is critical for sustainability of project outcomes. Linking farmers to markets does not necessarily require formal agreements, but achieving such formal linkages require greater focus on aggregation. Building a robust and effective M and E system is critical to facilitate effective monitoring, evaluation, and learning. Inadequate attention and measures to environmental and social safeguards compliance measures at the appraisal can pose serious challenges. Projects implemented in a low capacity environment and with demand driven interventions need better appraisal to avoid a slow start up and setting unrealistic targets for early years.
