AB  - Ratings for Competitiveness and Private Sector Development Project for Mozambique were as follows: outcomes were satisfactory, risk to global environment outcome was moderate, Bank performance was satisfactory, and Borrower performance was moderately satisfactory. Some of the lessons learned included: (i) the differences in World Bank (WB) and Government (Administrative Court (TA)) requisites and procedures for approval of procurement processes and financial auditing hindered the project performance; (ii) good Monitoring and Evaluation (M and E) is necessary for good project management; (iii) there were important benefits and efficiencies derived from the established partnerships with other donors; (iv) the project effectiveness can suffer if activities are not properly sequenced or if implementation timelines are curtailed by a delayed project start up; (v) the successful implementation of the matching grant provides valuable lessons for future World Bank Group (WBG) programs; (vi) ensuring the fast tracking of contract approvals by the TA given the experienced delays impacting the project implementation; (vii) making provisions for contingencies to avoid exchange rate risk, such as the Special Drawing Rights (SDR) or United States Dollars (USD) that the project experienced; and (viii) making provisions to ensure key Project Implementation Unit (PIU) positions remain active until the disbursement deadline.
