L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_ZR-DRC-_SME_Development_and_Growth_Project_--_P160806_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises (SME) Development and Growth Project for Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) were as follows: outcome and Bank performance were highly satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was high. Some lessons learned included: the achievements of the Project are a result of the multi-faceted instruments deployed under the Project, which reinforced each other and were tailored to the specific needs of different beneficiary groups. The analytical work carried out on micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs) and entrepreneurial ecosystem needs as well as the detailed preparation of SME instruments at the design stage were crucial for the Project’s success. The fragile and conflict-affected states (FCS) nature of context such as the DRC requires flexibility and modularity in the Project’s design and management. The Project employed a multi-faceted effective outreach model to inform and engage with women entrepreneurs that can serve as a model for similar projects in FCS contexts. The decentralization strategy to target select urban areas of interventions was critical to ensure proximity with the main beneficiaries (e.g., the MSMEs, including women and youth entrepreneurs); however, it requires engage with national and provincial stakeholders to establish ownership, build their capacity, and improve the enabling business environment. The reforms to strengthen the enabling business environment remain key to sustaining the development of MSMEs and value chains in strategic sectors of the economy. Procurement can become a major hurdle to overcome for multiple stakeholders. The SME hub pilot was successful, leading to the mobilization of United States (US) 15 million dollars in private capital, and can be scaled up as a key lever for the development of services, infrastructure, and partnerships crucial to the sustainable growth of MSMEs, supporting the overall ecosystem. The employment of private providers to implement activities was important for the Project’s success, particularly given the challenging context, while the systematic use of international-national consortiums facilitated knowledge transfer and local capacity building. In FCS contexts, private consortiums can provide crucial support with data collection, while capacity building to the Project Coordinating Unit (PCU) on M and E is also essential to ensure a well-functioning M and E system. The access to finance dimension is essential for supported firms to continue growing and giving them the freedom to use their banks for the reception of their cash grants, as opposed to employing only a selection of banks, can facilitate access to credit.
KW  - CONGO
KW  - Democratic Republic of
