AB  - Ratings for the Second Private Sector Competitiveness and Economic Diversification Project (PSCEDP II) for Lesotho were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: the high quality and committed leadership of the project management unit (PMU) was vital for successful project implementation and achievement of impact. Institutional support and strengthening of the business environment in low-capacity environments can be a difficult process, but it provides the foundations for more rapidly moving reforms later. Adoption of the underlying legal framework is a time consuming but critical factor in establishing new (or reforming existing) institutions. Enhancement of technological capacity and systems upgrades should be undertaken in the view of existing government capacity and resources available, to ensure their sustainability in the long run. Economic diversification policy in Lesotho benefits from not be exclusively centered on products that have preferential treatment in free trade agreements. The possibility of external shocks should be better captured at project design, especially considering the growing impact of climate change. Effective collaboration - among the participating World Bank teams and between the World Bank and the Government of Lesotho - is required due to the cross-cutting nature of private sector development and contributed to the success of the PSCEDP II.
