L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P151432_40030800_ICR_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Enhancing Shared Prosperity through Equitable Services Project for Ethiopia were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: in a decentralized context like Ethiopia’s, development of a platform for harmonized engagement on local service delivery is essential. The choice of scope and balance of sectors with a multi-sectoral service delivery operation should reflect national priorities and also be consistent with the relative importance of the sectors at the decentralized level. Improving service delivery outcomes at the local level relies on a viable funding framework. Equity considerations require targeting lagging or low-performing districts. Improving service delivery indicators is a long-term commitment and may not be linear. Improved service delivery relies not only on financing but also on the capacity of institutional mechanisms to translate that funding into service outcomes. Local government commitment to improving fiduciary management systems is key to sustaining transparency and accountability. Ethiopia Social Accountability Program (ESAP) is unique in its attention to the demand side of local governance and service provision, providing a number of lessons learned for social accountability efforts beyond the enhancing shared prosperity through equitable services (ESPES) context. Focusing on government environmental and social assessment systems rather than donor or project-specific requirements leverages significant impacts, well beyond the more limited focus of traditional investment projects. Information on results provides a critical feedback loop, and technology can be leveraged to enhance information sharing. In an environment where development financing is limited, with right government ownership a PforR supports sustained development. The use of a program-for-results (PforR) instrument proved critical to achieving results in such a complex cross-sectoral program, enabling countrywide systemic changes. A multi-sectoral PforR is by its nature a highly complex instrument and should be given effort and time for success. A PforR assumes a certain level of underlying stability in projecting results over time. Inclusion of an investment project financing (IPF) component mid-implementation supported the completion of disbursement linked indicator and disbursement linked result (DLI and DLRs), but added complexity to the PforR, particularly when DLI and DLR achievements are dependent on IPF activities.
KW  - Ethiopia
KW  - worldbank
KW  - ICR
