AB  - The overall outcome of the Local Governance and Service Delivery Project for South Sudan was moderately unsatisfactory with moderately satisfactory Bank performance and modest monitoring and evaluation quality. Lessons learned from the Project are: 1. In FCV (Fragile, Conflict, Violence) settings, the World Bank needs more flexible instruments. 2. Building in a robust risk management mechanism is crucial for operations in FCV settings. 3. It is possible to achieve results in FCV settings, especially through projects with a Community Driven Development (CDD) component. 4. Early post-conflict transitions present choices about how to appropriately sequence and manage trade-offs between supporting CDD and state-building. 5. Monitoring and evaluation (M and E) and supervision are challenging in FCV settings, and so need to be strengthened, including through providing task teams with detailed guidance on M and E design, emphasizing early third-party arrangements and iterative conflict and social analysis.
KW  - South Sudan
