AB  - Ratings of Third Phase of Promoting Basic Services Project for Ethiopia were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) Devolution of power and responsibilities to regions and woredas must be matched with resources; (ii) It is important to identify how to engage sectoral agencies within such a decentralized structure; (iii) Over time a decentralized system will need more diversified instruments than a single base general Block Grant to address issues of equitable access and quality; (iv) Improvements in basic services rely on important cross-cutting systems that may be overlooked in more narrow sectoral operations; (v) Specific lessons learned in respect to the screening tool designed for Ethiopia include the requirement for the procedure to be simple and, embedded within existing Environmental and Social Management Frameworks already in use; (vi) Improvements in basic services rely on important cross-cutting systems that may be overlooked in more narrow sectoral operations; and (vii) Despite the higher risks, there were significant advantages in PBS's reliance on national systems.
