AB  - The overall outcome of the Agricultural Productivity and Food Security Project for Burkina Faso is satisfactory, with satisfactory Bank performance and substantial monitoring and evaluation quality. A new Project Development Objective (PDO) indicator was introduced in 2014 to measure the increase in fish production in the targeted zones, with a target of 540 metric tons (MT) at the end of the project. The number and names of components remained unchanged throughout the project, but all three components expanded the scope of some activities (adding interventions or increasing the number of targets) and reduced the scope of others (transferring some activities to other projects or suspending an activity as warranted). Lessons and recommendations the Project provided are: (a) Scaling-up warrantage could enhance access to finance for farmers and improve food availability for rural markets; (b) Thorough planning is important to successfully implement an e-voucher distribution system; (c) Strengthen government capacity for better service delivery instead of bypassing government actors; (d) Multi-stakeholder innovation platforms improve the prioritization of investments and enhance coordination of the value chain.
