AB  - Ratings of Third National Fadama Development Project of Nigeria were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was substantial. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) Devolving management decision making and coordination to Management Committees of Fadama Community Association (FCAs), Desk Officers, and Facilitators in addition to the State Project Implementation Unit enhanced empowerment, social inclusion, participation, ownership, and sustainability; (ii) The presence of good local institutions is important to translate local aspirations into collective action, and it is a core element of a good Community-driven development (CDD) project; (iii) The project combined hard investments (FUG asset creation and community infrastructure) with soft technical support (capacity building and advisory support); (iv) Rather than pre-determining which assets to support, the project left the menu of options for investment support relatively open, to ensure that it would meet the actual demands of the project beneficiaries; (v) The design of Fadama III (and its predecessor projects) proved to be robust and agile; (vi) The inability to release counterpart funds in a timely way, exacerbated by the country’s financial constraints, affected timely implementation of programmed activities; (vii) The huge demand from states and local governments caused this national project to spread its efforts thinly and presented a challenge for implementation; and (viii) The Boko Haram insurgency in northern Nigeria nearly destroyed the Fadama legacy in that area. Collaborative engagements with specialized institutions (World Food Programme (WFP), Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) and Non-governmental organization (NGOs) were critical for delivering project interventions in this active conflict arena.
