AB  - Ratings of First and Second Fiscal Consolidation and Private Sector Support Development Policy Operations (DPO) were as follows: overall outcome was satisfactory, relevance of prior actions was satisfactory, and achievement of objectives was satisfactory. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) : A DPO can be used to help a country develop an adequate macroeconomic framework even in the absence of an IMF program; (ii) The use of the DPO instrument was critical in moving reforms forward that otherwise might have stalled; (iii) A technical assistance (TA) operation is an essential complement to a DPO to ensure follow through and, therefore, ensure implementation of reforms on the ground level, especially in a low capacity country like Mauritania; (iv) To achieve greater and faster impact of reforms, it is advantageous to have an actual activity/investment ready to go to put the reform into action; (v) Economic and financial constraints during or after a terms of trade (ToT) shock add pressure on governments to rapidly conduct reforms that otherwise would have taken longer to implement; (vi) Having strong ownership from the government and a champion within government of Mauritania (GoM) offered an excellent opportunity to achieve structural reforms and shifts in attitude, particularly during a time of high fiscal pressure; and (vii) Support to monitoring and evaluation is a long-term effort, particularly in a low capacity country.
KW  - Mauritania
KW  - worldbank
KW  - ICR
