L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_3W-Regional_Sahel_Pastoralism_Support_Project_--_P147674_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2022.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Regional Sahel Pastoralism Support Project for Western and Central Africa were as follows: outcome was moderately satisfactory, Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: since pastoral activities cut across countries in similar agro-climatic zones, addressing the regional dimensions of pastoralism is key; the division of responsibilities between the regional and the national level should adhere to the strict subsidiarity principle. Adequate financial arrangements, organized at regional and national level under the subsidiarity approach, are an important factor of efficiency and accountability of regional programs. Social engagement is a critical action in fostering ownership, mitigating conflicts and ensuring adequate delivery of services and implementation of infrastructures attuned to the needs of beneficiaries. Strengthening inclusion to get at the root-cause of conflicts should remain embedded in all projects targeting pastoralists; if this is not possible, projects should seek to work in tandem with other programs specifically addressing the problem. Diversification out of pastoral livestock activities to provide alternative livelihoods will become increasingly important in a context of growing risks and uncertainty faced by pastoralists. Adopting more flexible operational approaches, in contexts of insecurity, like the one prevailing in the Sahel, is a necessity in a fast-evolving environment.
