AB  - Ratings of Fostering Agricultural Productivity Project for Mali were as follows: outcome was moderately unsatisfactory, Bank performance was moderately unsatisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was modest. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) It is important to design the monitoring and evaluation system prior to project appraisal; (ii) More focused interventions are needed in complex implementation settings like Mali; (iii) Successful implementation through country systems requires a proper understanding of government systems, their weaknesses and capacity strengthening needs; (iv) Similarly, transitions from project to programmatic country approaches need to be supported only after assessing the feasibility and capacity to deliver and after securing the public stakeholders’ buy-in; (v) Well-designed synergies between implementation actors improve project delivery and build sustainability; (vi) Systemic risks (social, political and economic) need to be better integrated in design choices and adequate adaptation measures have to be developed; (vii) More crowding in of private sector in service provision is needed in Mali; and (viii) Projet d'Accroissement de la Productivité Agricole au Mal (PAPAM) is one of several projects in Mali that have used matching grants to finance microprojects.
