AB  - Ratings for the Third Productivity and Transparency Support Grant Project for Sierra Leone were as follows: outcomes were moderately satisfactory, the Bank performance was satisfactory, and the achievement of objectives was moderately satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: a key ingredient to successful participation of the private sector is the government’s conducive mindset and its willingness to vacate a space, as was demonstrated in seeds supply. It was also important to ensure the cooperation of the Ministry of Trade so that the private sector had what it needed to be able to import and supply seeds to farmers. It was also important that the government not vacate that role until the private sector was able to assume it. The success was evidenced by the number of approved private suppliers of seeds which substantially exceeded the target. There is need to strengthen institutional capacity to implement measures to attract more capital-intensive private investment in fertilizer production, distribution, and marketing. Moving from good plans and strategies to implementation may be difficult if the government’s ability to implement (to be contrasted with commitment) is overestimated, as was the case in the electricity sector. The success of the reform was thwarted by the government’s inability to install bulk meters in a timely way. The government’s commitment was good, but that did not translate into implementation capacity. Related to this shortcoming was that the WBG-supported IPF experienced delayed procurement of bulk meters. This also underlines the importance of close coordination with sector colleagues in the WBG, not just on policy reforms but also on input timelines. Asset declaration requirements can be made more effective if they apply strictly to officials who are in a position that deals with financial transactions. The series narrowed down what had been a blanket requirement for all government officials to declare their assets. This requirement was ineffective because it was not feasible administratively to enforce compliance with so many people, most of whom were not in financially sensitive positions. By focusing on only the most relevant officials, compliance with asset declaration increased substantially.
KW  - World
