AB  - Ratings for the Integrated Agricultural Development Project for Guinea were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: in a low-capacity context, building on existing projects’ operational framework is key to success rather than establishing a new Project Coordination and Implementation Unit (PCIU). It is critical to build the country’s preparedness for food insecurity and crises. Technical assistance that is critical for the project’s implementation needs to be recruited very early in the project cycle. Overall capacity for irrigation development needs to be critically assessed during project appraisal for projects with irrigation development activities. Innovations, such as revolving funds for the integrated maize program can amplify the impact of input support programs.
