L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_3W-Sahel_Irrigation_Initiative_Support_Project_--_P154482_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings of the Sahel Irrigation Initiative Support Project for the Sahel were as follows: Outcome was moderately satisfactory; Bank performance was moderately satisfactory; M&E quality was substantial. A regional approach anchored in capable institutions can mitigate fragility, conflict, and violence risks and generate durable public goods when its added value is explicitly defined and operationalized; future programs should clearly specify the regional public goods to be delivered, secure hosting and financing arrangements for knowledge platforms, and establish incentives and mechanisms that ensure country teams adopt and apply regional outputs. Differentiated irrigation typologies and strong integration between agriculture and water management are essential to control costs, improve performance, and ensure sustainability; projects should tailor cost ceilings, implementation arrangements, and risk management to each typology, treat agriculture–water integration as a core design element, and systematically document and compare cost and performance data across typologies to support adaptive portfolio management. Design realism, early implementation readiness, and clear co-financing arrangements are critical to efficiency in multi-country operations; teams should apply structured readiness checklists for procurement and implementation before effectiveness, define coordination mechanisms and contingency protocols with co-financiers based on clear milestones, and incorporate flexibility into results frameworks while maintaining a disciplined focus on a limited number of outcome-level indicators. These lessons point to practical recommendations that strengthen resilience, accelerate learning, and improve delivery in complex regional irrigation programs.
