L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P123112_40080017_ICR_2025.pdf
AB  - Ratings of the Transforming Irrigation Management in Nigeria Project for Nigeria were as follows: Outcome was moderately satisfactory, Bank Performance was satisfactory, and M&E Quality was substantial. Key lessons learned include that farmer led irrigation development (FLID) can effectively mobilize private on-farm investment when reliable water sources are assured, but future operations should systematically study, integrate, and scale FLID, explicitly accounting for its water demand within public scheme design to safeguard water productivity and system performance; prototype facility designs, such as for Farmers Management and Service Delivery Centers, must be adapted to local geotechnical and adverse weather conditions and supported by stronger supervision, client ownership, and accountability to avoid delays and quality issues; the absence of unified national dam safety standards led to inconsistent designs and approval delays, underscoring the need to transition to a programmatic, risk-based dam safety regime that institutionalizes regular inspections, emergency preparedness, and dedicated funding for remedial works; deeper engagement of State Governments is essential given their proximity to Water User Associations (WUAs) and experience with FLID, and future projects should formalize state roles in supporting and strengthening farmer organizations and ensuring continuity of reforms; scaling up the three-tier farmer institution model composed of Water User Groups, WUAs, and Apex WUAs requires an enabling legal framework to secure financial and managerial autonomy and to institutionalize participatory irrigation management, with advocacy for approval of WUA law and clear funds flow arrangements; demand-driven, applied research linked to farmer needs accelerates adoption, so future operations should prioritize practical innovations such as System of Rice Intensification and Typha management alongside coordinated training, demonstrations, and coaching; and operating in fragile and conflict-affected settings requires security-responsive project design that integrates upfront site-specific risk assessments, adaptive planning, and clear safety protocols, including the option to drop high-risk areas and the provision of protective measures for contractors and communities to maintain continuity of implementation.
KW  - Nigeria
