AB  - Ratings of Agro-Pastoral Export and Market Development Project for Niger were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was modest. Some of the lessons learned include: (i) physical investments need to be complemented by regulatory measures, in particular those that create a more friendly business environment and facilitate trade flows; (ii) time was insufficient to get to the point where fully developed Productive Alliances (PAs) would have emerged, in particular, as regards the develop of legal and enforceable contractual relations, in a context such as Niger where transactions typically remain informal; (iii) that matching grants work well to the extent that the investment is sustainable in the long-term (during the cruising period), meaning that the investor can take over project funding and renew investments after project closure, using the proceeds of his own sub-project; and (iii) regarding weirs and thresholds, sufficient attention needs to be given to properly target beneficiaries, and establish sustainable management and maintenance mechanisms involving their participation, which are the main ingredients for their sustainability.
