AB  - Ratings for the Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) Crisis-Response Development Policy Financing Project for Burkina Faso were as follows: overall outcome and achievement of objectives (efficacy) were moderately satisfactory, and relevance of prior actions was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: when designing a program in a crisis context, World Bank Group (WBG) teams should consider that there may be additional leverage to achieve more ambitious, longer-term reforms. At the same time, WBG teams should exercise caution when setting targets for indicators, particularly for standalone operations, that depend on establishing new data platforms. Bank teams can improve prospects for implementation and sustainability, including building client ownership, for which there is no substitute, as well as mitigating the risks of delays especially for a standalone operation, by using complementary operations, both investment policy financing (IPF) and development policy financing (DPF). A WBG team should be mindful of several potential success factors in establishing a new framework for dealing with a crisis. One strategy to increase the deployment and use of digital platforms is to create a kind of performance competition between ministries. Substantial progress can be achieved in the area of debt transparency in a short amount of time, when the WBG, development partners and the client are able to realize several critical success factors simultaneously.
KW  - Burkina Faso
