AB  - Ratings for the First and Second Economic Recovery and Resilience Development Policy Financing Project for Chad were as follows: overall outcome and achievement of objectives (efficacy) were moderately unsatisfactory, and relevance of prior actions was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: Chad’s fragility, conflict, and violence (FCV) context and its limited capacity to deal with shocks and accepting that there will likely be high risk-high reward tradeoffs. Formulation of RIs and targets - they should still be relevant and potentially achievable if external risks materialize, and they should be precise and measurable in a low data environment. Complementary technical assistance through complementary operations and analytics to support the government to implement and closely monitor reforms in a low institutional capacity environment. Complementing fiscal stabilization with reforms aimed at improving the capability of the state to protect the poor and vulnerable through human capital development and adaptive social protection programs. Building an engagement model with the government using virtual platforms that can be resilient during crisis situations that are more likely to occur in FCV contexts.
