AB  - Ratings for the First and Second Fostering Rural Growth Reform Development Policy Financing for Niger were as follows: overall outcome and achievement of objectives (efficacy) was moderately satisfactory, and relevance of prior actions was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: long-term engagement embodying both technical and political economy considerations is essential to preserve and build on reform gains. Despite some stakeholder opposition, it is possible to implement a cost-based tariff adjustment that improves an electric utility’s financial position, but the effort needs to be sustained. The creation of new arrears to local governments in 2018 and 2019 shows the need to put in place a strong framework that prevent the recurrence of this problem. Targeting of farm inputs through an e-voucher implementation program is a promising alternative to governments continuing to subsidize the procurement of farm inputs for all farmers but may require continued development partner support until it is established on a national basis. It can highly beneficial for the quality of the results framework and, later, for program evaluation, to retain a results expert during preparation to ensure a high-quality results framework that has a better chance of remaining stable throughout the program. In countries with significant security issues, it is beneficial for program implementation to have a strategy with both short- and long-term measures to lower the risk of disruption. When establishing a new institution, it is a good practice to help operationalize the new entity with pilot activities to build its capabilities.
KW  - Niger
