L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P164563_34292482_ICR_2024.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Refugees and Host Communities Support Project for Niger were as follows: outcomes were satisfactory, the Bank performance was satisfactory, and the monitoring and evaluation quality was high. Some lessons learned included: the integrated, multi-sectoral, geographically focused approach that advocated supporting the entire population affected by a crisis, regardless of their status (as refugees, IDPs, hosts), proved to be highly appropriate and effective in Niger. The robust remote monitoring system (GEMS), used as a design and implementation tool, helped PARCA to anticipate alternative project sites and to swiftly execute site switches; this was necessary when growing insecurity and/or beneficiary movement prevented project completion at a selected site and required shifting to another site. As the project needed to be aware of the dynamic security and FD situations in its target sites, it operated out of three implementation offices in three regions, which provided critical information on local context and flexibility to adapt to changing circumstances. Use of a national telecommunication operator for mobile cash transfers allowed the project to efficiently expand its geographic reach and increase its number of economic opportunity beneficiaries as the operator was able to provide services nation-wide. Well-designed procurement documents, with a breakdown of works by infrastructure type (education, health, water infrastructure, etc.) and by municipality, enable the recruitment of construction companies with solid knowledge of the local context regarding social and security issues, market-competitive pricing. Additionally, the integration of security costs into private sector bidding documents and contracts solicits viable bids and responsible service providers who deliver results. The use of standard Nigerien infrastructure designs promotes timely infrastructure completion, effective O&M and repairs with materials available at local markets, at local prices and with local know how, increasing the chances of realizing infrastructure work in other FCV areas within the country.
KW  - Niger
