AB  - Ratings for the Second Fiscal Reform Growth Project for Benin were as follows: overall outcome and achievement of objectives was moderately satisfactory, and relevance of prior actions was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: the use of the development policy operation (DPO) instrument was critical in moving reforms forward that otherwise might have stalled, particularly in line Ministries. DPOs can become a key instrument to support complex reforms in sectors of World Bank engagement and link transversal objectives. Longer term engagements are necessary to achieve sectoral overhauls. To achieve greater and faster impact of reforms, it is important to coordinate with other donors and Bank-financed investments loans. Having strong ownership from the government is the best way to achieve structural reforms and shifts in attitude. Innovative solutions and flexibility to support the government’s requests can bring additional benefits. Additional effort is needed to integrate the monitoring and evaluation (M and E) in government systems from the outset, particularly in a low capacity country.
