L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P161998_33886210_ICR_2022.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Kaduna Economic Transformation Project for Nigeria were as follows: outcome was satisfactory, bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was high. Some lessons learned included: On-the-ground support and the ability to make frequent trips to the state provided a solid understanding of the challenges and allowed the team to go relatively fast and build a rapport with the state counterpart, which meant decisions were often expedited. From the outset, there was ownership and buy-in from the state due to the ambitious plans already laid out by the state which the program keyed into. The KSDP (2016–2020), Sector Implementation Plans (2017–2019), Kaduna State Infrastructure Master Plan (2018–2050), and the Kaduna State Industrial Plan have all helped in setting the vision for the state as they show clearly where the state is, where it is planning to go, and how it can get there from all sectors. The aim of all these plans is to deliver on jobs, social justice, and prosperity. They stress the importance of fast-tracking private investments, which will lead to growth and job creation and strengthen fiscal sustainability of the state. The strength, integrity and commitment of the PIU in driving implementation is an important highlight of the program. The PIU was staffed and financed by the state government and the project manager of the PIU (who was a civil servant) was highly competent and driven, ensuring that the steps set out in the PAD were followed religiously. The Program Action Plan was robust and useful for addressing gaps in the government system and capacity issues. The project manager had the ability to motivate the civil servants and create buy-in to the PforR as well as the wider KSDP. The Kaduna governor carefully selected reform minded individuals within the civil service to head key agencies and deliver on their mandate.
