L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_TD-Chad_Value_Chain_Support_Project_--_P133021_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2021.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Value Chain Support Project for Chad were as follows: outcome was moderately unsatisfactory, Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: the project design should have incorporated more gender-related activities to contribute to the theory of change. In low-income fragility, conflict, and violence (FCV) countries with difficult political environments the governments’ administrative burdens should have been better anticipated and mitigated. When dealing with site construction that entails risks to inhabitant’s safety or environmental damages, it is compulsory to assign environmental and social development specialists during the project’s identification phase and onboard a safeguards expert in the project unit in addition to the focal point in a ministry. To avoid disproportions between objectives and allocated resources, the targets at project design stage must derive from precise and technical studies and analytical underpinnings. Weak monitoring and evaluation (M and E) framework and lack of sound system for accurate data collection affected assessment of results and their attribution to achieving the project objective (for example, the volume of meat produced in slaughterhouses and slaughter areas in target zones). Monitoring indicators in the results framework should be realistic, attributable, and achievable during implementation. It is highly recommended to increase sustainability and client’s ownership in a fragile and politically volatile environment like Chad by ensuring participation of private sector stakeholders as critical actors. When dealing with sensitive matters as healthy nutrition, the project preparation must be derived from sectoral technical studies. Resources allocated through the matching grant facility (MGF) must be based on a thorough analysis of small and medium-size enterprises (SMEs) needs. Strong leadership by task team leader (TTL), profound technical skills, strategic vision, integrity, and innovative approach to problem solving are key characteristics contributing to a successful project restructuring.
