AB  - The Support to Economic Diversification Project of the Republic of Congo had a moderately satisfactory overall outcome, a moderately satisfactory performance by the Bank and the monitoring and evaluation was modest. The lessons learned were: (1) When the realities of a fragile state, together with complicated political economy and macroeconomic conditions, are not taken into consideration neither when designing a project nor when steering it, this can critically affect project outcomes. (2) Importance of a “pilot-type” project for future WB operations in the Republic of Congo. (3) Instability at the PIU level and lack of appropriate technical staff can affect the timeliness of delivery of activities and ultimately the ability to analyze the impact of said activities. (4) Design of the Matching grant activity, including the number of steps in approval for the processing and overall method for management, caused delays in implementation of the activity and an inability for some approved firms to eventually participate. (5) The inclusion of such a large percentage to come from counterpart funding posed significant risks to achievement of project outcomes.
