AB  - Ratings for the Land Policy Improvement and Implementation Project for Cote d’Ivoire were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: social inclusion was central to the success of Land Policy Improvement and Implementation Program (PAMOFOR), particularly through the introduction of the new clarification phase and formal land use contracts (LUCs). Sustained, high-level commitment and support from champions within the World Bank (WB) and government were critical to achieving the dual objectives of strengthening institutions while simultaneously delivering land records. Broader impacts, such as increased investment, productivity, and access to credit, often take time to materialize following land registration and typically depend on complementary reforms. However, the additional time, funding, and coordination invested in implementing the IE proved worthwhile, as it demonstrated early results that validate the Project’s theory of change (TOC). The project’s success was largely attributable to the digitization and streamlining of rural land registration procedures, which increased efficiency and scalability, and substantial counterpart financing, which is pivotal for sustainability.
KW  - Cote d'Ivoire
