AB  - Ratings for the Climate Smart Agriculture Support Project for Niger were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: local governments can be good entry points for engaging on community initiatives regarding climate change adaptation, but their limitations need be adequately assessed at appraisal and constantly monitored during project implementation. An e-voucher system can be a useful tool in delivering agricultural input subsidies to the poor, but it requires a critical understanding of the political economy. A climate change adaptation program is a truly collaborative effort of different agencies. Several factors are critical for successful project outcomes in a fragile environment.
