AB  - The overall outcome of the Obsolete Pesticides Project for Mali is moderately satisfactory, with satisfactory Bank performance and substantial monitoring and evaluation quality. The Project offers several lessons: 1. A highly skilled technical advisor on disposal operations to support the country on developing bidding documents, vetting bids, monitoring Environmental Management Plans (EMPs), and monitoring collection, transport, and site cleanup is essential; 2. Ambitious and complex data management systems always fall short; 3. Priorities for disposal, risk reduction, and prevention of future accumulation of stocks should be clearly prioritized in project design; 4. The Government’s ability to manage pesticides could be enhanced by mainstreaming the issue into the design of projects in other sectors rather than just in disposal projects; 5. A sustainably-financed structure for pesticide management in Mali is essential for management over the long term and to avoid the re-accumulation of new OP (Obsolete Pesticide) stocks.
