AB  - Ratings for the First, Second, Third, and Fourth Poverty Reduction Support Operations and Supplementals for the Second and Third Operations for Liberia were as follows: outcome, achievement of objectives (efficacy), and Bank performance was moderately satisfactory, and relevance of prior actions was satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: good fiduciary practices require sustained repetitive measures to become ingrained in government operations. Good communication with all stakeholders (government, legislature, civil society) from the start is needed to avoid preparation and implementation delays. It is wise to keep the range of policy areas flexible so that new areas of reform can be pursued if circumstances warrant. Capacity for reform in countries like Liberia, which experienced a lack of rule-of-law based governance over several years requires heavy technical assistance (TA) to support a successful reform program.
