L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_LR-Liberia_Land_Administration_Project_--_P162893_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2023.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Land Administration Project for Liberia were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: in contexts of institutional and legal transition, adopting a flexible, broadly defined project design that is not conditioned on the passage of potential legislation changes can enable projects to build capacity and support early progress towards achieving the project development objective (PDO) before adapting to the evolving framework in due course. Strong engagement with the donor community and civil society through the establishment of a multi-actor platform and the appointment of a director responsible for land sector stakeholder coordination can help spur implementation progress and maximize the impact of project activities. Support for the creation of a new land agency in a fragile context requires long-term support that extends beyond a 5-year project, at the risk of jeopardizing recent achievements.
KW  - Liberia
