TI  - Niger - Public Sector Capacity and Performance for Service Delivery Project
AU  - World Bank
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/08
PB  - World Bank
M3  - Implementation Completion and Results Report
UR  - http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/099020008082241967
L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P145261_33881396_ICR_2022.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Public Sector Capacity and Performance for Service Delivery Project for Niger were as follows: outcome was moderately unsatisfactory, bank performance was moderately unsatisfactory, and monitoring and evaluation quality was modest. Some lessons learned included: in fragile countries with limited implementation capacity, the Government’s technical capacity and readiness to implement major ICT solutions should be assessed and confirmed before project approval. In the case of PCDS, a successful project outcome could not be achieved without the successful implementation of a modern HRMIS integrating HRM with payments. However, there was a lack of analytical underpinning at the time of approval, including on the political economy factors related to cleaning up the database and improving accountability and transparency in the management of the public wage bill in Niger. At the end, a new HRMIS could not be deployed. Efficiently using project preparation advances (PPA), non-lending TA, or existing operations to set the foundation for upcoming ICT activities, in general, and politically sensitive ones, is critical to ensure readiness during implementation. In addition, hiring technical expertise in project management under a PPA has proven to be effective in accelerating project implementation. Furthermore, the World Bank should provide hands-on support to governments to implement ICT solutions (and be selective on the number of ICT solutions). Due to the inherent complex nature of ICT activities, procurement processes in fragile settings are often long and equally complex, and further complicated by relatively short project cycles of 4-5 years (and usual resistance from numerous actors). Therefore, in addition to setting up the foundation for upcoming ICT activities through PPAs and existing operations, World Bank support is required to help the Government recruit qualified technical expertise in project management. For this reason, hands-on extended implementation support (HEIS) should be offered to the Government to expedite the procurement process, ensure the recruitment of qualified consultants, and contribute to adequate contract management during implementation.
