L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_CM-Cameroon_Social_Safety_Nets_--_P128534_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2023.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Social Safety Nets (SSN) Project for Cameroon were as follows: outcome and Bank performance was satisfactory and monitoring and evaluation (M and E) quality was substantial. Some lessons learned included: it takes time to build government ownership for the SSN agenda. The institutional aspect of building the SSN may be better addressed through the full suite of World Bank instruments rather than solely through investment project financing (IPF). Surge capacity for the Project Implementation Unit (PIU) is required in instances where safety net projects are supporting emergency response. There are benefits in adopting an integrated approach to support refugees and host communities across the portfolio. Factoring in childcare arrangements is critical in ensuring that women are able to benefit equally from public works activities. Cash transfers have the potential for several secondary impacts, which are not usually monitored but are nevertheless critical. Developing an effective communication strategy from the outset, which cuts across different levels of government and other stakeholders, is essential.
KW  - Cameroon
