AB  - Ratings for the Second Local Development Program Support Project (LDPSP 2) for Chad were as follows: outcomes were unsatisfactory, risk to development outcome was high, Bank performance was unsatisfactory, and Borrower performance was unsatisfactory. Some lessons learned included: project development objectives (PDOs) should be less ambitious and more realistic for countries with limited implementation capacity and a fragile political environment. Bottom-up development projects that use community driven development (CDD) approaches are challenging to implement and scale up, because they require extensive support with respect to capacity building. One aspect that should be especially emphasized as it is crucial to the success of decentralization is the participatory process. Hence the need for such expertise as trained community facilitators on the ground. LDPSP 2 has done some headway on that front that need to be preserved. Project remedies should be clearly identified as different from overall dialogue between the Bank and the Borrower. Realistic implementation risk assessment should result in considering alternative institutional arrangements.
