L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_GW-Guinea-Bissau_Biodiversity_Conservation_Project_--_P122047_Implementation_Completion_and_Results_Report_2016.pdf
AB  - Ratings for the Biodiversity Conservation Project for Guinea-Bissau were as follows: outcomes were satisfactory, the risk to development outcome was substantial, the Bank performance was satisfactory, and the Borrower performance was also satisfactory. Some lessons learned included: intense and sustained supervision is appropriate for high-risk environments but does not need to be costly or always direct, face-to-face encounters with country counterparts and stakeholders. The project demonstrated how to ensure sustainable financing for the conservation of globally-important biodiversity in a situation of fiscal constraints. Guinea-Bissau is an emblematic example of uniting donor collaboration around a longer-term vision with the Bank as catalyst, providing relatively small financing with technical assistance to leverage the commitment and resources of diverse entities to achieve a weightier result. It is recommended that the Guinea-Bissau case be used to promote discussion in the Bank on how to ensure minimum financing for protected areas management in the many African countries where this continues to be a struggle despite the significant environmental services such areas provide. Stability of the Bank and Client core teams and the depth/mutual trust of their engagement have been highly advantageous. Such stability can have major advantages over time especially for technically challenging projects in difficult country conditions. The Bank and Client teams remain largely in place with a strong commitment to the over-arching vision, an excellent working relationship based on trust, and the benefit of institutional memory. It is recommended that this stability be preserved to the extent possible through continued Bank financial support until IBAP and the FBG are clearly able to walk on their own.
KW  - Guinea-Bissau
