L1  - C:\Users\mlolita\OneDrive - CGIAR\WP2_Evidence Synthesis\Grey Literature\Data\Project_doc\Worldbank\Docs\2015_2026\worldbank_P116557-P127822_24205173_ICR_2015.pdf
AB  - The First and Second Development Policy Loan in Support of the Plan Maroc Vert received a moderately satisfactory outcome rating with significant risk to development outcome. The Bank received a satisfactory rating for its performance while the Borrower received a moderately satisfactory performance rating. No restructurings took place during the life of this project. Country developments led to three changes in the agreed prior actions for the second operation. These changes were: (a) the substitution of an agreement on the management model at Berkane for the previously proposed action on three wholesale market pilot projects. The concept remained the same but essentially the target was reduced from three to one. (b) The addition of the executive decision on market liberalization for red meat to the proposed action on concession to the private sector of modernized municipal slaughterhouses. (c) The substitution of the transmission of the draft laws creating the Regional Agriculture and Rural Development Offices (ORDARs) for the previously proposed action raising irrigation tariffs. There were several lessons learned from this project including the following: (1) A development policy loan (DPL) works best when it stems from a home-grown reform program with strong ownership within government. (2) A further strong value of Bank support under a DPL is to help create a platform for agencies that otherwise may have divergent agendas. (3) The linking of a DPL to a sectoral medium-term expenditure framework (MTEF) aligns incentives for both the finance ministry and the line ministry, and provides investment resources to accompany and help implement reforms that otherwise might not take place or might not yield their intended returns. (4) In the case of Morocco, submission of draft legislation to the Government General Secretary (SGG) may be inadequate assurance that a reform will be promptly executed. (5) Evaluation of a DPO is constrained by the short time scale, particularly for a two loan series, where the final evaluation occurs only twelve months after the second set of prior actions. (6) There is a need  and an opportunity  to accompany some reforms with project-style guidance and investment.
