AB  - Ratings for the Second Water Sector Investment Project for Tunisia were as follows: outcomes were unsatisfactory, the risk to development outcome was substantial, the Bank performance was unsatisfactory, and the Borrower performance was also unsatisfactory. Some lessons learned included: the project will have greatly benefited from a solid institutional analysis. Such an analysis, possibly in the form of ASA, will have provided all stakeholders with a comprehensive, level playing field. Often, it makes sense to do a portfolio-wide institutional assessment, particularly as most public sector staff have the same incentives and face similar issues and challenges. During preparation and implementation of an irrigation project, assess carefully the amount of water available over time. Several irrigation sub-projects recorded lower water availability compared to the forecast in the detailed study. In some new perimeters, the target area was increased following the detailed study due to pressing demand from the population. In both cases, the water availability per hectare was reduced, limiting the opportunity for the farmers to intensify their production and thus find in agriculture a way out of poverty. While it is true that sometimes more farmers benefitted from the project, many of them remained in a situation of semi-subsistence agriculture.
